{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15561"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.02,0.04,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112062"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2720"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5800"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112062"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the Burns Unit outpatient clinic for follow-up two months after sustaining partial thickness burns to his right upper limb from a cooking incident. He underwent successful split-thickness skin grafting three weeks ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His skin grafts have healed well without infection. He describes constant burning pain and hypersensitivity with itchiness in his right arm that is worse at night and interferes with sleep. The pain is not relieved by simple analgesics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pregabalin","Ketamine infusion","Oxycodone sustained release","Lidocaine patch","Tapentadol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of post-burn neuropathic pain, characterised by burning sensations and hypersensitivity. The pain pattern and description suggest central sensitisation following thermal injury and subsequent surgery. Gabapentinoids (Pregabalin/Gabapentin etc) are considered first line for management of post-burn neuropathic pain and pruritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregabalin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for post-burn neuropathic pain. It reduces central sensitisation by modulating calcium channels and decreasing the release of excitatory neurotransmitters. It has good evidence for treating neuropathic pain and can improve sleep.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetamine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe, refractory cases of neuropathic pain and requires admission to hospital. It would not be appropriate as first-line treatment in this outpatient setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxycodone sustained release\u003C/strong\u003E is not first-line treatment for neuropathic pain. While opioids may be needed in the acute phase of burn injury, long-term use should be avoided due to risks of dependence and side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELidocaine patches\u003C/strong\u003E may help localised neuropathic pain but are not as effective for larger areas of involvement. They are typically used as adjunct therapy rather than first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETapentadol\u003C/strong\u003E is a dual-action analgesic with \u03bc-opioid receptor agonist and noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor properties. While it may have some efficacy in mixed pain syndromes, it is not considered first-line for neuropathic pain and carries similar risks to other opioids regarding dependence and side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of post-burn neuropathic pain often requires a multimodal approach including medications, physical therapy, and psychological support. Early recognition and treatment is essential to prevent the development of chronic pain syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuropathic pain is common following burn injuries and often requires multimodal analgesia including gabapentinoids.","Early recognition and treatment of post-burn neuropathic pain can prevent chronic pain syndromes.","Physical therapy and rehabilitation are essential components of post-burn pain management."],"references":["Stanton E, Won P, Manasyan A, Gurram S, Gilllenwater TJ, Yenikomshian HA. Neuropathic Pain in Burn Patients-a common problem with little literature: A Systematic Review. Burns. 2024 Feb 28. Available online at ; https://tsaco.bmj.com/content/tsaco/6/1/e000810.full.pdf","The role of analgesics in chronic noncancer pain [published 2020 Dec; amended 2023 Jun]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {2025 Aug 24}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94128","links":{"self":"